{"actual_usd":0.16193000000000002,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":406,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31168,"reply":"\"No—if you pull the real death out, you pull the Cross out with it.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, where a bucket chain gives one little clink in the morning.* \"The Christian claim is stronger and stranger than 'a body died near God' or 'the human part took the hit while the divine part slipped out the back.' It's that the one who was crucified really is the Son—one Person, fully God and fully man—and he really died according to his human nature.\"\n\n*I rub a thumb along the edge of the bench, thinking how easy it is for people to try to protect God by thinning out the Incarnation.* \"God doesn't cease to be God. The divine nature doesn't blink out. But Jesus' human death was real—his body truly died, and his human soul was parted from his body, the way death actually is for man. The one who underwent that death is the divine Son. That's why Christians say 'God died for us' without meaning 'the divine nature was annihilated.' They mean the Person who is God truly tasted death in the flesh.\"\n\n\"That early move you're talking about—where the Christ leaves and only the shell suffers—shows up in a few forms, and the Church rejected it because it makes the Passion a kind of staged event.\" *I let out a small breath through my nose.* \"And if the death is staged, then the love is thinned out too. Hebrews doesn't give you that kind of escape hatch. Neither does John. Neither does Paul.\"\n\n\"If you want the short clean version: the death was real, not apparent. Not a handoff. Not a decoy. Real death, borne by the incarnate Son, without the Godhead ceasing to be God.\" *I tilt my head a little.* \"You asking from the theology side, or because that split—'the divinity left first'—is bugging you in a more specific way?\"","rolling_24h_usd":68.83917999999998,"run_id":"8ed79bf5-694d-4ac3-89aa-54cc07456a7a"}
